<dl id="n12003d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12003d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12003d"> 3(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> s&apos;emporta-t-il</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Il arrive aussi que les verbes trop longs, mis en incise, soient cacophoniques. Songez qu&apos;il y a pl&eacute;thore de verbes de la premi&egrave;re conjugaison, qui risquent d&apos;envahir les autres. D&apos;o&ugrave; ces horreurs: <i><mark>s&apos;emporta-t-elle, lamenta-t-il</mark></i>. On dirait des noms de produits chimiques! <br><font color="green">[It also happens that verbs that are too long, when used in an embedded clause, become cacophonic. Especially when there is a plethora of words of the first conjugation, which risk to invade the others. Thus horrors like: <i><mark>s&apos;emporta-t- elle, lamenta-t-il</mark></i>. They sound like the names of chemical products!]</font> <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 244</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
